  "prompt": "Are there statutes that address money laundering?",
  "response": "Yes, there are several statutes that address money laundering in the United States:\n\n1. The Bank Secrecy Act (BSA) of 1970\n- Requires financial institutions to report suspicious transactions\n- Mandates reporting of cash transactions over $10,000\n\n2. The Money Laundering Control Act of 1986\n- Made money laundering a federal crime\n- Established criminal penalties for money laundering activities\n\n3. The USA PATRIOT Act of 2001\n- Enhanced anti-money laundering regulations\n- Expanded reporting requirements\n- Increased cooperation between financial institutions and law enforcement\n\n4. The Anti-Money Laundering Act of 2020\n- Updated and modernized existing anti-money laundering laws\n- Increased penalties and enforcement mechanisms\n- Expanded reporting requirements for cryptocurrency and digital assets\n\nAt the federal level, money laundering is primarily prosecuted under 18 U.S. Code \u00a7 1956 and \u00a7 1957, which define different types of money laundering offenses and establish criminal penalties.\n\nState laws also exist that complement federal statutes and provide additional mechanisms for prosecuting money laundering activities.\n\nThese statutes aim to prevent criminal proceeds from being integrated into the legitimate financial system and to detect and prosecute financial crimes.",
